# Rust Documentation Standards

All Rust code in sqlite-anki must be documented following [rustdoc conventions](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/how-to-write-documentation.html).

## Required documentation

| Item | Style | Required |
|------|-------|----------|
| Crate root | `//!` or `#![doc = "..."]` | Yes — purpose, main types, WASM/SQLite context |
| `pub mod` | `//!` module doc | Yes — responsibility and how it fits the crate |
| `pub` fn, struct, enum, trait, type, const | `///` doc comment | Yes — every public item |
| `pub(crate)` helpers | `///` | Yes if logic is non-obvious |
| Private fns / impl blocks | `///` or `//` | Yes when behavior, invariants, or SQLite/WASM details are not obvious from the name |
| `unsafe` blocks | `///` + `# Safety` section | Always — justify every safety precondition |
| `no_mangle` / FFI exports | `///` + `# Safety` | Always — SQLite C API contract |

Do not merge undocumented public API. Add docs in the same change as new code.

## How to write `///` comments

1. **First paragraph** — one clear sentence: what it does (summary line for rustdoc).
2. **Following paragraphs** — when needed: inputs, return value, side effects, errors.
3. **Standard sections** (use only when relevant):
   - `# Examples` — runnable ` ```rust` doctests for public API where practical
   - `# Errors` — variants or codes returned
   - `# Panics` — when and why
   - `# Safety` — required for `unsafe` and FFI

Use Markdown links and intra-doc links: `` [`Embedder`] ``, `` [sqlite3_vtab] ``.

Do **not** use JavaDoc-style `@param` / `@return`. Rustdoc uses prose and `#` sections only.

## Examples

```rust
// ❌ BAD — public, no docs
pub fn embed(text: &str) -> Result<Vec<f32>, AnkiError> { ... }

// ✅ GOOD
/// Embeds `text` into a fixed-size sentence vector using the bundled ONNX model.
///
/// Returns a vector of length [`EMBED_DIM`]. Empty strings and whitespace-only
/// input are treated as absent text and return [`AnkiError::EmptyInput`].
///
/// # Errors
///
/// Returns [`AnkiError::Inference`] if Tract fails to run the session.
pub fn embed(text: &str) -> Result<Vec<f32>, AnkiError> { ... }
```

```rust
// ❌ BAD — module with no overview
pub mod hnsw;

// ✅ GOOD
//! HNSW approximate nearest-neighbor index for one `TEXT VECTOR` column.
//!
//! Each virtual table column owns a [`ColumnIndex`]. Indexes are serialized to
//! the backing store on commit and loaded in [`ColumnIndex::open`].
pub mod hnsw;
```

## Non-obvious blocks

Short `//` comments are required for tricky control flow (virtual table callbacks, query planning, transaction rollback) when a reader cannot infer intent from names alone. Prefer *why* over *what*.

```rust
// Rebuild the candidate set once per statement: xFilter may run before
// xBestIndex hands us the MATCH constraint for parameterized queries.
```

## WASM / FFI

Document ownership, pointer lifetimes, and thread assumptions for anything crossing the Rust/C or Rust/JS boundary. SQLite extension entrypoints must state when they are called and what they register.

## When editing

- New `pub` items without `///` → add docs before finishing the task.
- Changed behavior → update the doc comment in the same edit.
- Prefer extending existing module `//!` docs over duplicating context in every function.
